english:
  title: Official Decree Appointing Jung Gong-su as Commander of the Divine Tiger Guard
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since the age of the Five Hegemons, in nations that wield the sword, the truest way to inspire the courage of thousand-strong armies is to select worthy generals and entrust them with command. The finest way to demand results from ten thousand soldiers is to reward those whose merit stands paramount.

    Our official Jung Gong-su harbored from youth the ambition to bring peace and prosperity to his realm, and his name spread with renown both near and far. When sent as magistrate to govern a distant region, like the Duke of Shao beneath the acacia tree, the people flourished under his benevolence. When dispatched to inspect a province, like Fan Fang holding the reins of governance, the petty officials trembled in awe. When the Jin kingdom fragmented and the burden of defending the northern frontier fell upon his shoulders, he moved with swift resolve. Against the ravages of roving brigands he brought swift capture and complete suppression. To generals in distress seeking refuge, he offered trust and sustenance. Those whom he aided returned with gratitude, and in their good fortune they remembered his kindness, offering him intelligence of value whenever occasion arose. Though outwardly this appeared as defense against foreign powers, in truth it was safeguarding our own household from thieves. Such wisdom in reading the times, such generosity in offering aid—these are the fruits of his foresight.

    Therefore we elevated him to commander of a thousand, bestowing upon him office in the Imperial Censorate. Before long we granted him the rank of the third tier and delegated to him authority over the Imperial Secretariat. Soon after, he grasped the symbols of command and returned to pacify the borderlands. In the campaign tent he devised strategies that crushed treachery in its infancy. Through dispatched proclamations to barbarian lands he captured those engaged in treason and brought them to justice. Truly these are feats of uncommon excellence—how could ordinary precedent suffice to honor them?

    Therefore we overlook his seniors and grant him advancement in rank, that the realm of officials might know awe, and that the standards of integrity might be upheld. His deeds of loyalty have proven worthy of our discerning selection. Now we issue this mandate from the inner court: let him assume his rightful place as Supreme Commander. By special imperial decree we confer upon him this honor.

    Hark! That rank be the whetstone upon which the world is sharpened—this is our prerogative as sovereign. That loyalty thread through the days in service to the throne—this is the heart of the faithful minister. Let him cherish the honor bestowed upon him, and thereby strengthen all the more his steadfast integrity.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Hegemons (五覇) refers to the five most powerful lords during China's Spring and Autumn period—figures of legendary leadership and military prowess.
  - key: ''
    value: The Duke of Shao and Fan Fang were celebrated exemplars of benevolent governance in classical Chinese history, known for their compassion toward the common people.
  - key: ''
    value: The Divine Tiger Guard (神虎衛) was an elite military unit in Korean kingdoms, and appointment to its command represented significant honor and military authority.
  - key: ''
    value: This text is an official decree (官誥) written in the classical Chinese style, employing elaborate parallelism and allusion typical of formal government documents of the Goryeo period.
